title: For Sale/Trade:  Pre 1958 S&W 5 screw 44 Magnum 4 inch revolver
postcontent: I contacted S&W and was told this firearm is so old the serial number is not in their database. In 1958 S&W started using letters along with numbers in their serial numbers. It also does not have a model designation... just 44 magnum on the barrel. It is a 5 screw pinned barrel and recessed cylinder model. It has what are referred to as "coke bottle" factory grips or Diamond grips. The serial number is stamped on the frame under the grips and on the inside of the barrel shroud. For it being at least 50 years old its in pretty tight and decent shape. Bluing is probably 80 percent in my opinion. On the left side of the frame is a previous owners name and the year 1971 engraved. As S&W told me, even if I wanted them to refinish it they wouldn't, as it would destroy collector value. $999.00 cash or trade, and we can go from there.

title: For Trade:  LMT Defender 2000 AR-15 for your AN/PVS-14 or 7
postcontent:
What I WANT:
Gen 3 or better Night Vision System (NVS), like a PVS-14 / 7 or OPMOD, etc. It can be rail-mounted, helmet / binoc, or even handheld monocular (order of preference). I'm also open to something in FLIR / Thermal as well. Whatever it is, it needs to have some REAL life left in it, not some 10 year old, battle-scarred beater. For the right unit I'm willing to add boot. 

What I HAVE:
One of my AR's is a gorgeous LMT Defender 2000 that has had fewer that 500 rounds put through it (all top-shelf brass, no steel-case crap). I have a few high-end AR's but this is the only one that has been a virtual safe queen. There literally is not a single use mark on it, it looks brand new. It's an all-original LMT, purchased earlier this year, that I have tastefully upgraded with useful, high-end parts -- a Troy Battlesight rear flip-up BUIS (dead-on co-witness), a Troy Carbine-Length quad-rail, an ERGO grip, Spike's billet trigger guard, a Magul CTS buttstock and B.A.D. lever, a LaRue Tactical buffer tube and Tubb Precision spring, and an AIMPOINT PRO up top that co-witnesses with the Troy BUIS and standard front A2 sight post. I think I still have the original LMT box as well, but will have to confirm that.

At **today's** prices this rifle is easily over $2,000 to duplicate, using the best street prices.

This isn't some cheap Rock River, Bushmaster, Windham Walmart rifle or a Frankenbuild. No, this is a beautiful rifle, and is ready to be YOUR go-to battle rifle. If you're interested feel free to email or call. I'm in Northeast Alabama, and I have my own 150-yard rifle range if you want to come by and give her a test-drive. Just bring your NVS along, and we can talk turkey.

I'm NOT interested in selling rifle outright, unless you know someone who has a NVS and he's willing to do a 3-way deal.

Brendan -- (256) six 6 zero - one 5 six 6

title: For Sale:  Cobray LHC Street Sweeper Ladies Home Companion 45-70 / 410
postcontent:
For Sale – This is a Cobray (SWD, Later known as Cobray and Leinad), Ladies Home Companion (LHC), AKA- The Mini Street Sweeper. It is made in the USA and a copy of the South African design.

* It is chambered in 410 shotshell , 45-70 government rounds, or .45 Long Colt.

* It is officially classified by the ATF as a pistol/revolver that’s why it has no stock or forward pistol grip. I guess in a way you could call it a revolver since the drum does not remove for reloading.

* It holds 12 rounds with a built in drum.

* These units are NOT listed as a destructive device. When the Street Sweeper became listed as a Destructive Device, Cobray used some of their tooling to create the LHC.

* The 45-70 pistols do have a grooved barrel and operates exactly like the 12 gauge units.

* This unit was completely refurbished. The main spring and trigger group were degreased and re- oiled to ensure a long service life. The unit looks and functions like new. Very few of these units exist and this is a wonderful addition to any firearm collection.

* Weighs about 12 pounds, has a 25 lbs trigger pull and can all be release in about 3 seconds.

* Very few of these are on the open market.

* These were made by Cobray, which also produced the Street Sweeper shotgun.

* If you”re wondering why Cobray chose that name (Ladies Home Companion), it’s because the Street Sweeper’s name was partially why it got targeted by politicians. Rather than choose something menacing, they went with something friendly.
